{
  "card_id": "power_of_three",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Power of Three",
  "aliases": [
    "Accumulation Manipulation Distribution",
    "Accumulation, Manipulation, Distribution",
    "AMD",
    "PO3",
    "po3",
    "Power of 3",
    "power of 3"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A three-phase price delivery model: Accumulation (consolidation range), Manipulation (liquidity sweep opposite true direction), Distribution (directional move to target). Forms OHLC candle structure and often maps to Asia (accumulation), London (manipulation), New York (distribution) sessions.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a consolidation range (accumulation) by marking the range high and low using candle bodies (not wicks), typically formed during Asia session or sideways price action.",
    "Map the timing: Asia session corresponds to accumulation, London session to manipulation, and New York session to distribution, using kill zones as time anchors.",
    "Identify manipulation as an aggressive breakout from the accumulation range that sweeps liquidity (prior high/low) and then produces an aggressive displacement back into the range, distinguishing it from a genuine breakout.",
    "Confirm manipulation with a change in state of delivery (CISD) where price closes back through the opposing series of candles that formed the sweep, or with a market structure shift.",
    "On a higher-timeframe candle, manipulation forms the wick and distribution forms the body closing in the true direction: a candle with a long opposing wick indicates manipulation only, while a small wick may indicate both phases in the same candle.",
    "Validate manipulation with confluences: the sweep reaches into a higher-timeframe PD array (order block, fair value gap, equilibrium) or shows SMT divergence.",
    "Anticipate distribution as an expansion move opposite the manipulation, targeting the opposite range boundary, previous day high/low, or standard deviation projections (-2 to -2.5 primary, -4 extended) measured from the manipulation leg.",
    "Use lower timeframes to visualize the accumulation–manipulation–distribution sequence for precise entry placement.",
    "The pattern can be observed on multiple time frames simultaneously (e.g., a 4-hour Power of Three containing an intraday session-level Power of Three).",
    "Bullish structure produces an Open-Low-High-Close candle; bearish structure produces an Open-High-Low-Close candle."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Power of Three provides a roadmap for timing entries. After accumulation and manipulation are confirmed, traders anticipate distribution in the opposite direction. Entry is taken on a retracement into an order block, fair value gap, or OTE within the manipulation leg, with stop at the manipulation extreme. Targets are the opposite side of the accumulation range, prior day high/low, or standard deviation projections (-2 to -2.5 primary, -4 extended). Preferred setups feature strong displacement and confluences with PD arrays or SMT divergence, avoiding low-probability breakouts and indecision days.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering during accumulation or before manipulation has occurred.",
    "Mistaking the manipulation sweep for a genuine breakout and trading in its direction.",
    "Expecting distribution without first confirming a manipulation (liquidity sweep and aggressive return/CISD).",
    "Taking entry on a bare range retest without waiting for an order block or change in state of delivery confirmation.",
    "Using wicks instead of candle bodies to mark the accumulation range boundaries.",
    "Trading without a higher-timeframe bias or draw on liquidity, turning AMD into pattern trading without context.",
    "Placing stops too tight at the manipulation extreme rather than on the broader daily high/low when targeting the full range.",
    "Anticipating large New York distribution expansion when most of the daily range was already created in London (or when both sides of Asia range were taken), leading to low-probability consolidation.",
    "Failing to wait for aggressive displacement back into the range; treating any move out as manipulation without a return.",
    "Entering before the manipulation wick has formed and a protected swing/low is confirmed via change in state of delivery.",
    "Expecting large expansion moves on days lacking higher-timeframe direction or high-impact news (e.g., CPI, FOMC), which produce indecision.",
    "Confusing a reversal candle 2 (large opposing wick) with a continuation candle 2 (small wick), leading to trading the wrong candle.",
    "Projecting standard deviation targets from the wrong anchor; the manipulation leg must be drawn from the extreme to the swing point that produced it.",
    "Treating London's initial directional move as the true move rather than recognizing it as potential manipulation or consolidation.",
    "Entering in the direction of the manipulation sweep instead of waiting for the Change in the State of Delivery to confirm the true distribution direction.",
    "Failing to recognize that the Power of Three can operate across multiple time frames simultaneously (e.g., missing a 4-hour Power of Three that contains the intraday session structure)."
  ],
